<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written Evidence Submitted by the Joint Industry Board for the Electrical Contracting</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BRC52</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">vidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ubmitted by the Joint Industry Board for the Electrical Contracting </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Joint Industry Board for the Electrical Contracting Industry </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(JIB) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">operates an Electrotechnical Certification Scheme (ECS) for electricians and related work disciplines in England, Wales and Northern Ireland</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The ECS covers all sectors of the el</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ectrical market – industrial, commercial and domestic</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are over 111,000 current valid card holders in the UK at present</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The JIB proposes to work with all Competent Person Schemes by providing access to the ECS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for Qualified Supervisors and other indiv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">iduals who undertake work for registered companies</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A primary objective of the JIB is to operate in the public interest (JIB Rules, clause 3). The JIB considers that the further promotion of the ECS card in the domestic market is directly aligned with this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">objective</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Joint Industry Board for the Electrical Contracting Industry</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Joint Industry Board for the Electrical Contracting Industry (JIB) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is a not for profit organisation. It </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">was established in 1968 by The Electrical Contractors’ Association and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the Electrical, Electronic, Telecommunication and Plumbing Union (now part of Unite the Union).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Further information on the JIB is available on its website at </span><a href="http://www.jib.org.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">www.jib.org.uk</span></a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Electrotechnical Certification Scheme</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Electrotechnical Certification Scheme (ECS) is jointly owned by the Joint Industry Board (JIB) and its sister organisation, the Scottish Joint Industry Board (SJIB).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The primary aims</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the Scheme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to set standards for individual competence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, to ass</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ess competence against the standards within the Scheme and to accredit competence through the issue of ECS cards to individuals.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Scheme developed from the JIB and SJIB Grading Systems, which were introduced in 1968 by the JIB and in 1969 by the SJIB.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he UK Register of Electricians was established in 1993 to accredit electricians who could demonstrate competence equivalent to the standards of the National Vocational Qualification (N/SVQ) at Level 3.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 1999 the JIB Grading System was merged with the UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Register of Electricians to form </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">one industry recognised scheme under </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Electrotechnical Certification Scheme (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ECS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">). Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> scheme became available to all individuals who could demonstrate that they met the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">required </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">standard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The ECS was affiliated to the Construction Skills Certification Scheme (CSCS) in 2002 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">following the introduction of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Health and Safety Assessments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. These were implemented following a call in February 2001 by the Deputy Prime Minister for the construction in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dustry to improve its safety record.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A total of over 111,000 cards are held across the UK, with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 98,000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cards currently held by individuals based in England, Wales and Northern Ireland, of which over 48,000 are Installation Electrician</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A further 13,000 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cards are held by individuals based in Scotland.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Further information on the ECS is available on its website at </span><a href="http://www.ecscard.org.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">www.ecscard.org.uk</span></a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Part ‘P’ of the Building Regulations</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The introduction of Part ‘P’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the Building Reg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ulations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in 2005 set minimum standards for the first time for electrical installation work in dwellings.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Competent Person Schemes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">took the domestic sector forward</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> introduc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing the registration of Qualified Supervisors by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lectrical companies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Qualified Supervisor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> responsible for signing off work and in doing so warranting that the work has been undertaken in accordance with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all parts </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the Building Regulations and that the electrical installation has been executed in accordance with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">wiring regulations (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">BS 7671</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The use of initial and subsequent annual assessments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the electrical business </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Competent Person Scheme helps to set and maintain standards.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The concept of Competent Person Schemes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which ensure that companies comply wit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h Building Standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is however incomplete without the accreditation of the competence of the individuals who actually undertake the work.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It should be noted that whilst the Qualified Supervisor is responsible for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">signing off work under Part ‘P’, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">they</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> may</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> not have personally undertaken the work. This point is particularly important in the case of electrical installations and repairs because much of the work is hidden</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">14.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The JIB offer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to work with the Competent Person Schemes to accredit the competence of e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ach individual who undertakes electrical installation work in the domestic sector in England and Wales within the scope of Part ‘P’ of the Building Regulations.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">15.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In each case the individual’s qualifications and experience will be considered in accordance wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">th the rules of the ECS and an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">appropriate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ECS card will be issued to that individual.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">16.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The ECS will then become the UK wide scheme for the accreditation of the competence of electricians</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This will provide c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">onfidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> consumers and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">clarity for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the industry. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Benefits of this Proposal</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">17.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This proposal is intended to deliver the following benefits:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The consumer will benefit from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the introduction of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">established</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> standards of competence for each individual who undertakes electrical work in dwelling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, thus providing confidence that all work </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> undertaken professionally and to the appropriate standards of electrical safety</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Addressing individual competence will help to improve standards of installation and thus reduce the risk of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dangerous</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> electrical </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">installations and the consequences which flow from this, which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">may </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">include electrocution </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fires.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Competent Person Schemes will benefit from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recognition </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of common standards of individual competence by a scheme administered by a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fit independent organisation which has 45 years experience of setting standards and accrediting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">competence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of electrician</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Individuals working in the domestic sector will receive recognition of their individual competence through the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> accreditation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to one established </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">industry </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">scheme</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">4 December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>